sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKES TOP AFTER WINNING BY AN INNINGS.
West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons took four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead of the county championship.
Their stay at the top may be short-lived, however, as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey came close to victory and Kent made up lost time in a rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After being bowled out for 83 at Grays Road Somerset in the morning, Leicestershire extended their first innings to 94 points before being bowled out for 296 and England batsman Andy Caddick took three for 83.
With 213 points, Somerset got off to a solid start in their second innings before Simmons stepped in to bowl them out for 174.
However, Essex look certain to reclaim top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Sooch gave them a firm grip in the game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who is considered surplus to England's one-dayers, hit 158 shots, his first century in the Championship this season, as Essex reached 372 and took an 82-shot lead into the first innings.
By the end Yorkshire had turned into a 37-point advantage but off-spinner Suh had dashed their hopes by taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man dumped by England, continued to silence his critics by following up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hope Mark Butcher, who made 70, while Surrey finished on 429 for seven, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire went on to chase their first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody took six for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a 233 first-innings lead.
After the disappointment of the opening day's match, heavily influenced by the weather conditions, Kent upped their gear to knock Nottinghamshire out for 214.
They were held to 84 by Paul Johnson but former England fast bowler Martin McCaig took four for 55.
By the end of the game, Kent reached 108 points on three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER IS NAMED ENGLAND CAPTAIN.
The world's most expensive footballer Alan Shearer was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for 15 million pounds ($23.4 million), succeeds Tony Adams, who led the team during the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer is taking over the captain's armband on trial, but new coach Glenn Hoddle has said he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take up the post.
"I'm sure there won't be a problem, I'm sure Alan is the man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could do it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was up for it and really wanted it.
"In four days it is very difficult to come to a 100 percent conclusion about such a thing...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows about the situation in the team, even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 partner Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the squad with an injury on Friday.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BLOCKED AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd must play its next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during a 1-0 home defeat on Saturday that ended Rotor's brief period as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on September 3.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup has been fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position with 11 games to play.
Being three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, the Volgograd players have a game in hand on the leaders and two ahead of the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran takes to the ring on Saturday in another attempt to continue his long career.
The 45-year-old Duran faces little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
The fight, which was Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, was billed as "The Return of the Legend" and Duran still talks like he's in his prime.
This match is to prepare me.
I'm not going to retire," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer admit the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, middleweight and junior middleweight - is close to the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he's on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the greatest boxers in the world," said Panama Boxing Association president Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will secure him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against the Panamanian boxer in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN MAKE TWO TURNS UNDER THE SPOTLIGHT.
Andre Agassi avoided disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliWay Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of upsets at the US Open.

The 11th seed in Washington failed to repeat his miraculous comeback from Wimbledon, losing to the red-hot "Wildcard" Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour and 51-minute battle on the stadium court.
On the adjacent grandstand, tenth seeded Rios lost to another player associated with Wimbledon, bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to claw his way out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole, winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the evening belonged to the novices.
Washington, who rallied from a 1-5, two-set deficit in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semifinal, looked poised for another sensational turnaround.
O'Brien, who won his first pro title in New Haven two weeks ago, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set, after which Washington came back into the match.
"I just kept telling myself, keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen," said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my composure and was proud of myself for it - normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
O'Brien, a former U.S. college national champion, strung together 17 aces to hold off an indomitable Washington.
The fifth set continued on serve until the sixth game when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, plated a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan plated two aces to hold serve at 5:2, then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand at 40:0.
"You just keep fighting and trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he tightened up a little bit at some points," Washington said. "
But I thought he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose temper tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a suspension from this year's tournament at the All England Club, argued over calls and taunted fans during his live tango with Rios, which lasted two hours and 24 minutes, in the stands.
The boisterous crowd cheered the distracted Chilean and booed the scrawny American, who absorbed all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," says the 104th-ranked Tarango. "
I think I played very well tonight, I was very focused. "
The match went into a tiebreak in the third set, which the American won 7:5 to the horror of the spectators.
"I love the crowd if they boo me every day.
It fuels me and makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"My best tennis was in college, when fraternities were flooding me with beer.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
I think I played very badly.
It was hard to play at night.
The balls were moving very fast.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball like I do during the day.
I play American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the court. "
At the end of the match, Tarango gives out sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then moves his body in front of the section with Rios fans to greet them.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango says of the fans. "
At the same time they rejoice openly against me.
After I won, I thought I could give them a little shine. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading rusher at quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to rise above center, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl participant, Cunningham has amassed 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful Philadelphia fans for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
Selected in the second round in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a contract with a broadcaster.
